items.text: **Atalanta Bergamasca Calcio**, commonly known as just **Atalanta**, **Atalanta Bergamo** or the abbreviation **Atalanta BC**, is an [[LINK|lang_en|Football_in_Italy|Italian football]] club based in [[LINK|lang_en|Bergamo|Bergamo]], [[LINK|lang_en|Lombardy|Lombardy]]. The club currently plays in [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_A|Serie A]], having gained promotion from [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_B|Serie B]] in [[LINK|lang_en|2010–11_Serie_B|2010–11]].
They are nicknamed the *Nerazzurri* and the *Orobici*.
Atalanta play in blue-and-black vertically striped shirts, black shorts and black socks.
The club stadium is the 21,300 seat [[LINK|lang_en|Atleti_Azzurri_d'Italia|Atleti Azzurri d'Italia]].

In Italy, Atalanta is sometimes called *Regina delle provinciali* (queen of the provincial clubs) to mark the fact that the club is the most consistent among clubs not based in a metropolitan area, having played 56 times in Serie A (11th overall for number of participations in the top division), 28 times in Serie B and only once in [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_C1|Serie C1]].

The club won the [[LINK|lang_en|Coppa_Italia|Coppa Italia]] in 1963 and reached the [[LINK|lang_en|Cup_Winners'_Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] semi-final in [[LINK|lang_en|1987–88_European_Cup_Winners'_Cup|1988]], when it was still competing in Serie B. This is still the best ever performance by a non-first division club in a major [[LINK|lang_en|UEFA|UEFA]] competition (together with [[LINK|lang_en|Cardiff_City_F.C.|Cardiff City]]). Atalanta also participated twice in the UEFA Cup, reaching the quarter-finals in [[LINK|lang_en|1990–91_UEFA_Cup|1990–91]].
History
The club was founded in 1907.
A football club had existed in Bergamo since 1904.
Founded by Swiss immigrants, it was known as *Foot Ball Club Bergamo*.
The rival Atalanta club grew out of a division between different sporting societies in the town.

The name is taken from the [[LINK|lang_en|Atalanta|female athlete]] of [[LINK|lang_en|Greek_mythology|Greek mythology]]. The [[LINK|lang_en|Italian_Football_Federation|FIGC]] was unimpressed with the new club and did not officially recognize them until 1914. The current club is the result of a merger between Atalanta and a third team called Bergamasca. The first, black and white coloured and the second wearing a blue and white shirt, merged in 1924 as *Atalanta Bergamasca di Ginnastica e Scherma 1907*. The team moved to the site of the current ground, on the Viale Giulio Cesare, in 1928.
Atalanta joined the Italian league in 1929.

The club first reached [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_A|Serie A]] in 1937, but was relegated immediately. The club returned in 1940 and remained in Serie A until 1959; after a single season in [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_B|Serie B]], the club was promoted and lasted a further decade in Serie A before relegation in 1973 led to an uncertain period of promotion and relegation between the two levels.
The club achieved its highest position so far in 1948, finishing in fifth place, a feat only bettered in 2017.

In 1981, the club fell into [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_C1|Serie C1]], a blow which revitalised the club. The team returned to Serie B the next season and made it back to Serie A in 1984. The club's form in Serie A remains uncertain, as it was relegated in 1987, 1994, 1998, 2003, 2005 and 2010. After a change of ownership, [[CITE|2|http://gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Atalanta/04-06-2010/atalanta-tornato-percassi-704252674135.shtml]] in 2011, Atalanta immediately came back to Serie A, where it has been ever since.

In terms of titles the club has won little, their sole silverware is the 1963 [[LINK|lang_en|Coppa_Italia|Coppa Italia]]. The club has had a few good runs in Europe, on several occasions being eliminated by the eventual winners.

[[LINK|lang_en|Wales|Welsh]] club [[LINK|lang_en|Merthyr_Tydfil_F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]] caused an upset in the [[LINK|lang_en|1987–88_European_Cup_Winners'_Cup|1987–88 European Cup Winners' Cup]], beating Atalanta 2–1 in the first leg of their first round match at [[LINK|lang_en|Penydarren_Park|Penydarren Park]]. After winning the second leg 2–0 in Bergamo, Atalanta went on to reach the semi-finals, losing to eventual winners [[LINK|lang_en|KV_Mechelen|Mechelen]] of [[LINK|lang_en|Belgium|Belgium]], but in the process becoming one of only two teams in the competition's history to reach the penultimate round while playing their football outside of the national top flight league. Oddly enough, the only other team to do so being Merthyr Tydfil's countrymen at [[LINK|lang_en|Cardiff_City_F.C.|Cardiff City]].

Atalanta reached the [[LINK|lang_en|UEFA_Europa_League|UEFA Cup]] quarter-finals in the 1990–91 season, losing to local rivals [[LINK|lang_en|Inter_Milan|Internazionale]], who went on to beat another Italian side, [[LINK|lang_en|A.S._Roma|Roma]], in the final to win the tournament. The club never played European club competitions after 1991, although turned down the opportunity to play in the [[LINK|lang_en|UEFA_Intertoto_Cup|UEFA Intertoto Cup]] in [[LINK|lang_en|2000–01_Serie_A|2001]] after finishing in seventh place in Serie A, regional rivals of [[LINK|lang_en|Brescia_Calcio|Brescia]] played the tournament instead, losing only in the final against French side [[LINK|lang_en|Paris_Saint_Germain_F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].

In recent years, the club was relegated after the [[LINK|lang_en|2002–03_Serie_A|2002–03]], [[LINK|lang_en|2004–05_Serie_A|2004–05]] and [[LINK|lang_en|2009–10_Serie_A|2009–10]] seasons, but gained the promotion to Serie A after only one season every time.

In [[LINK|lang_en|2011–12_Serie_A|2011–12]], Atalanta was docked six points in the league table due to the outcomes of an [[LINK|lang_en|2011–12_Italian_football_scandal|Italian football scandal]]. Nevertheless, the club managed to secure another year in Serie A by gaining 52 points in 38 games. The following year, for the same reasons, the club was docked two points in the league but avoided relegation reaching the 15th spot in the final table. In the [[LINK|lang_en|2013–14_Serie_A|2013–14]], Atalanta enjoyed another strong campaign, finishing in 11th place.

Atalanta struggled during the [[LINK|lang_en|2014–15_Serie_A|2014–15 season]] despite some impressive results. At the [[LINK|lang_en|2014–15_Atalanta_B.C._season|beginning of the season]], manager [[LINK|lang_en|Stefano_Colantuono|Stefano Colantuono]] committed his future to the club. On 4 March 2015, however, he was sacked after a poor run of form which left Atalanta only three points above the relegation zone. He was replaced by [[LINK|lang_en|Edoardo_Reja|Edoardo Reja]], who secured the club's status in Serie A for [[LINK|lang_en|2015–16_Serie_A|2015–16]], where Atalanta [[LINK|lang_en|2015–16_Atalanta_B.C._season|finished 13th]].

In [[LINK|lang_en|2016–17_Serie_A|2016–17]] Atalanta stuttered at the beginning of the season and new coach [[LINK|lang_en|Gian_Piero_Gasperini|Gian Piero Gasperini]] was on the verge of dismissal, but with an amazing run of positive results the team secured an impressive 4th-placed finish with 72 points, thus celebrating its return to Europe after 26 years, qualifying for the [[LINK|lang_en|2017–18_UEFA_Europa_League|UEFA Europa League]].

Youth System

The Atalanta youth system consists of four men's teams that participate in separate national leagues ([[LINK|lang_en|Campionato_Nazionale_Primavera|Primavera]], Allievi Nazionali A and B, and Giovanissimi Nazionali) and two that participate at a regional level (Giovanissimi Regionali A and B). [[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]]
The first person who was committed to set up the Atalanta youth teams was Giuseppe Ciatto.
Every organisational aspect was dealt with and resolved by him, and he also took care to train the various teams.
In 1949 Atalanta won the Campionato Ragazzi.

In the late 1950s former Atalanta player Luigi Tentorio (then Special Commissioner of the club) felt the need to start investing more systematically in youth: he decided to create a real youth sector, with its own independent structure from the first team.

The youth sector was entrusted to Giuseppe Brolis, who created a partnership with various clubs in the [[LINK|lang_en|Veneto|Veneto]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Friuli|Friuli]] regions, building a network of scouts and young coaches.

A crucial step in the history of the Bergamo youth sector took place in the early 1990s when the president [[LINK|lang_en|Antonio_Percassi|Antonio Percassi]] implemented a new investment policy, especially at the youth level. He managed to convince Fermo Favini to leave [[LINK|lang_en|Calcio_Como|Como]] and entrusted him with the responsibility of the youth sector.
The Atalanta youth system not only continued to increase the production of players for the first team, but began to win several honours in the most important national leagues.
From 1991 to 2014, the various youth teams have won 17 national titles.

Apart from successes at youth level, the Atalanta youth system is also one of the most highly regarded in Europe: according to a ranking by the study centre in Coverciano, Atalanta have the top youth system in Italy and the sixth in Europe, behind [[LINK|lang_en|Real_Madrid|Real Madrid]], [[LINK|lang_en|Barcelona|Barcelona]] and three French teams. The parameters used were the amount of first division players produced by the club. [[CITE|23|http://rovigooggi.it/articolo/2009-03-24/dal-vivaio-alla-prima-squadra-un-percorso-educativo]] In the 2007–08 season, 22 players from Atalanta's youth played in [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_A|Serie A]], 32 in [[LINK|lang_en|Serie_B|Serie B]] and 3 abroad. [[CITE|23|http://rovigooggi.it/articolo/2009-03-24/dal-vivaio-alla-prima-squadra-un-percorso-educativo]]
In 2014, a global study of the "CIES Football Observatory", placed the Atalanta youth system eighth place in the world, with 25 former youth players who play in the top 5 European leagues.
[[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]]
Presidential history

Atalanta have had several presidents (chairmen) ([[LINK|lang_en|Italian_language|Italian]]: *presidenti*, [[LINK|lang_en|Literal_translation|lit.]]'presidents' or [[LINK|lang_en|Italian_language|Italian]]: *presidenti del consiglio di amministrazione*, [[LINK|lang_en|Literal_translation|lit.]]'chairmen of the board of directors') over the course of their history. Some of them have been the main shareholder of the club. The longest-serving chairman is [[LINK|lang_en|Ivan_Ruggeri|Ivan Ruggeri]], who was relieved of his duties after he suffered a stroke in January 2008, being replaced by his son Alessandro [[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]] who was named chairman of Atalanta in September 2008. Alessandro's father was unable to manage the team due to the consequences of the stroke. [[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]] In June 2010, after another relegation to Serie B, Alessandro Ruggeri sold his share of the club to [[LINK|lang_en|Antonio_Percassi|Antonio Percassi]], who became the new chairman of Atalanta. [[CITE|2|http://gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Atalanta/04-06-2010/atalanta-tornato-percassi-704252674135.shtml]]

items.text: Supporters
Atalanta's supporters are considered very loyal.

When Atalanta plays at the [[LINK|lang_en|Stadio_Atleti_Azzurri_d'Italia|Atleti Azzurri d'Italia]], the supporters in the *[[LINK|lang_en|Curva_(stadia)|Curva]] Nord* (*North Curve*) encourage the team with their chants during the entire match.

The biggest rivalry is with the neighbouring supporters of [[LINK|lang_en|Brescia_Calcio|Brescia]], [[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]] and there are strong rivalries also with supporters of [[LINK|lang_en|Hellas_Verona_F.C.|Verona]], [[LINK|lang_en|Genoa_C.F.C.|Genoa]], [[LINK|lang_en|ACF_Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[LINK|lang_en|A.S._Roma|Roma]], [[CITE|14|http://calciogoal.it/completati-i-lavori-allo-stadio-dellatalanta-impianto-senza-barriere-gioiello-architettonico-foto]] [[LINK|lang_en|S.S._Lazio|Lazio]], [[LINK|lang_en|S.S.C._Napoli|Napoli]], [[LINK|lang_en|A.C._Milan|Milan]], [[LINK|lang_en|Inter_Milan|Internazionale]], [[LINK|lang_en|Torino_F.C.|Torino]]; while there has been a long-standing friendship with [[LINK|lang_en|Ternana_Calcio|Ternana]], fans of the German [[LINK|lang_en|Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] club [[LINK|lang_en|Eintracht_Frankfurt|Eintracht Frankfurt]] and fans of the Austrian club [[LINK|lang_en|FC_Wacker_Innsbruck|Wacker Innsbruck]].
On special occasions, Atalanta supporters display a very large black and blue flag called *Bandierù* which covers the whole *Curva Nord* stand.
